source_id: STP754-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_5th Volume_017_chunk4

evidence_span: The thermal neutron capture cross section of Excel is initially higher than Zr-2.5Nb, but since the capture cross section of tin and molybdenum decreases with irradiation due to transmutation, the average cross section of Excel over 30 years is 13 percent less than $\mathbf { Z r } { - } 2 . 5 \mathbf { N } \mathbf { b } \left[ I \delta \right]$

source_id: STP754-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_5th Volume_017_chunk4

source_id: STP754-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_5th Volume_017_chunk4
evidence_span: Measurements in the three principal directions on annealed and cold-worked/stress-relieved Zircaloy-2 slab materials provided evidence that growth is a constant-volume process up to about $\bf { 6 8 0 ~ K }$

source_id: STP754-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_5th Volume_017_chunk4
evidence_span: The growth strains were shown to be determined by the crystallographic texture, that is, proportional to $( 1 - 3 f _ { d } ^ { c } )$ , where $\mathcal { f } _ { d } ^ { \mathcal { c } }$ is the fraction of basal poles, $f ^ { \epsilon }$ , in the direction d.

source_id: STP754-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_5th Volume_017_chunk4
evidence_span: The growth strains for annealed and cold-worked Zircaloy were large relative to previously reported data, were similar in magnitude, were strongly dependent on irradiation temperature, and varied linearly with fluence over the range investigated.

source_id: STP754-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_5th Volume_017_chunk5
evidence_span: Irradiation growth in zirconium alloys has been characterized by the dependence of dimensional change on irradiation fluence and temperature and on texture, grain shape, heat treatment, and degree of cold work
